{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595463"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:04:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:04:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15358"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15358"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.04,0.08,0.08,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8049"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68537"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8049"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15358"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53994"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"},{"type":"tags","id":"11019"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19544"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19548"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68537"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe natural history of chronic hepatitis B infection progresses through several distinct phases. Laboratory findings vary in each phase and help guide management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best characterises the immune active phase of chronic hepatitis B infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High viral load with elevated liver enzymes and inflammation","High viral load with normal liver enzymes","Low viral load with elevated liver enzymes","Low viral load with normal liver enzymes","Undetectable viral load with elevated liver enzymes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe immune active phase of chronic hepatitis B is characterised by \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh viral load with elevated liver enzymes and inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E. During this phase, the immune system recognises and attempts to clear infected hepatocytes, resulting in liver damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other phases of chronic hepatitis B infection:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh viral load with normal liver enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern is seen in the immune tolerant phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow viral load with elevated liver enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - This may be seen during seroconversion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow viral load with normal liver enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents the inactive carrier phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUndetectable viral load with elevated liver enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern is not typical of any chronic hepatitis B phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe immune active phase may last for weeks to years and can lead to progressive liver damage if untreated. Regular monitoring of viral load and liver enzymes is essential during this phase.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The immune active phase of chronic hepatitis B is characterised by high viral load, elevated liver enzymes, and active liver inflammation.","During the immune active phase, the immune system attempts to clear infected hepatocytes, which can lead to liver damage if untreated.","The natural history of chronic hepatitis B includes immune tolerant, immune active, inactive carrier, and reactivation phases."],"references":["Mehta P, Grant LM, Reddivari AKR. Viral Hepatitis. 2024 Mar 10. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32119436","Lok AS, Pawlotsky JM. Viral hepatitis at a crossroad. Gastroenterology. 2012 May;142(6):1261-3. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2012.03.007. PMID: 22537431","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Scienc","Song JE, Kim DY. Diagnosis of hepatitis B. Ann Transl Med. 2016 Sep;4(18):338. doi: 10.21037/atm.2016.09.11. PMID: 27761442; PMCID: PMC5066055"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53994"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15358"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53994"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T20:17:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T20:21:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8049"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68537"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"da